      <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-[#64748B] max-w-3xl">
        Component scores normalised 0 to 100 within each dimension. Composite = 40% Victimisation + 25% Volume + 35% Severity.
      </p>

      <div class="space-y-6 text-body text-[15px] leading-[1.7] mt-8">
        <p>Ages 50 to 64 rank first because they are the only cohort scoring above the midpoint on all three dimensions simultaneously. Ages 65+ rank fourth despite topping the severity dimension. Remove the underreported volume component and the cohort moves to second; the 65+ ranking is a data infrastructure problem as much as a risk ranking.</p>
        <p>The 50 to 64 finding survives every reweighting of the index. The 65+ finding does not. The federal data infrastructure systematically underestimates fraud exposure among the cohort that loses the most per incident.</p>
      </div>
